detailResultFields.value: Large Instrumental Ensemble - UBC Concert WindsOpen only to 1st and 2nd year undergraduate students (see MUSC 350C for 3rd and 4th year registration; 550C for graduate registration).Open to non-music majors and secondary concentrators who are performers on woodwinds, brass, or percussion. Open to other students by audition, with credit, as stipulated by their faculties. May be repeated for credit. The ensemble rehearses MW 6-8:00 and makes four performances each year, with the majority of rehearsals and concerts taking place in the Chan Centre. While every effort is made to place students in appropriate ensembles based upon audition results, those taking this course as an elective are advised to have an alternate course ready in the unlikely case where an ensemble placement is not available. Entrance by audition each September. For more info: http://music.ubc.ca/student-ensembles

detailResultFields.value: Includes a variety of ensembles performing music of the Medieval, Renaissance, and Baroque periods. Alternative rehearsal times may be organized if necessary. For registration conflicts, please contact the instructor.For 1st and 2nd year undergraduates (see MUSC 457A for 3rd and 4th year registration; 557A for graduate registration).NON-MUSIC STUDENTS with relevant skill, knowledge, and experience may request permission of the instructor to register. detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
All BMUS ORIN Strings students must register in MUSC 160A in their lower years. The course focuses on small ensemble combinations (trios, quartets, etc.) which will be formed in September. A regular coaching time will then be assigned to each small ensemble during the indicated hours. Each ensemble should also schedule regular rehearsal time(s) during these hours.

For 1st and 2nd year undergraduates (see MUSC 360A for 3rd and 4th year registration; 560A for graduate registration).

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value: BMUS PIAN students register in MUSC 161A.For 1st and 2nd year undergraduates (see MUSC 361A for 3rd and 4th year registration).Small ensemble combinations will be formed in September, and regular coaching times will then be assigned during the indicated hours. Each ensemble should also schedule regular rehearal time(s) during these hours. Students registered in MUSC 161A who also wish to register in MUSC 157 (Early Music Ensembles) or MUSC 163 (Contemporary Players) may do so, but will need to contact the Music Advisor (music.advisor@ubc.ca) for a registration override. Students needing additional chamber ensemble credit may be able to register for additional credit in September, pending approval from the Division.BMUS General Music students with a concentration in Piano may apply to enroll in MUSC 161A upon completion of MUSC 167 with a minimum grade of 88. Approval from the instructor of MUSC 167 and permission from solo piano instructor are also required. Final permission to enroll is not guaranteed, and will be given by the Chamber Music Coordinator (in consultation with the Director, as needed). Requests for admission should be sent to Professor Rena Sharon (rena.sharon(at)ubc.ca). General Music piano concentrators allowed to register in MUSC 161A will normally be permitted to take it only once, for 2 credits. They may apply to take MUSC 161A a second time if they have obtained a minimum grade of 88 in the course.

detailResultFields.value: AFRICAN MUSIC & DANCE ENSEMBLEFor 1st and 2nd year undergraduates (see MUSC 466D for 3rd and 4th year registration; MUSC 565D for graduate students).OPEN TO NON-MUSIC STUDENTS: How do I register for ensembles? The course is open to all without audition.This course/ensemble introduces drumming techniques, dances and other artistic expressions of Africa. Through the instruments, the voice, the dance movements and other visual art forms and paraphernalia, this class/ensemble brings to the stage a unique African theatrical experience. The course/ensemble may be repeated for credit. It will include public performances (concerts and lecture demonstrations). Also as a practical way of preparing for the main concert, students may be requested to participate in other performances on or off campus as the need may arise.

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
Delivery Mode -This is a synchronous multi-access course. Students are expected to meet on the days and times listed, either in-person or online. All courses labelled ‘multi-access’ offer students the choice of completing the course online, in-person, or using a mix of both. In-person attendance is NOT required, but the option to attend in-person is available. Lectures may be streamed from a classroom and/or uploaded online after class.

Waitlist Policy -All waitlists will follow a first come, first serve policy, unless specified otherwise. Once a course is full, its status will be changed to “Waitlist” and students who register will be automatically added to the waitlist.

A general statement about Dr. Margolis' PHIL101: https://www.margolisphilosophy.com/phil101-blurb.html
FAQs about Dr. Margolis' PHIL101: https://www.margolisphilosophy.com/101-faq.html
